<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,198,400]" pageId="4" pageNumber="213">
Known from 
<collectingCountry box="[288,505,302,329]" name="Papua New Guinea" pageId="4" pageNumber="213">Papua New Guinea</collectingCountry>
and Tasmania where it is rare, growing on the ground over bryophytes or thin peaty soil. This species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[558,701,338,364]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Xylographaceae" genus="Lambiella" kingdom="Fungi" pageId="4" pageNumber="213" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="applanata">
<emphasis box="[558,701,338,364]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="213">L. applanata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[715,859,338,364]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Xylographaceae" genus="Lambiella" kingdom="Fungi" pageId="4" pageNumber="213" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="umbratilis">
<emphasis box="[715,859,338,364]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="213">L. umbratilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the newly described 
<taxonomicName box="[1144,1270,338,364]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Xylographaceae" genus="Lambiella" kingdom="Fungi" pageId="4" pageNumber="213" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="plumbea">
<emphasis box="[1144,1270,338,364]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="213">L. plumbea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<tableCitation box="[1328,1410,338,364]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[136,224,159,183]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 1. Comparison of salient features of the Lambiella applanata group. including the newly described L. plumbea." pageId="4" pageNumber="213">Table 1</tableCitation>
). A full description is provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Coppins, B. J. &amp; Kantvilas, G." box="[481,802,374,400]" pageId="4" pageNumber="213" pagination="35 - 48" refId="ref7270" refString="Coppins, B. J. &amp; Kantvilas, G. (2001) Four new species of Rimularia Nyl. (Agyriaceae). Bibliotheca Lichenologica 78: 35 - 48." type="journal article" year="2001">Coppins &amp; Kantvilas (2001)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
